The Smash Brothers Documentary

Video Game Documentary - Produced by Travis Beauchamp, Published by East Point Pictures in 2013 - English narration


Information
------------------------------

The documentary provides a fantastically engaging look into the world of early competitive Melee fighting tournaments, as well as a broad look into how itÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s evolved today with the introduction of big venues like MLG and EVO.

Most interestingly, the feature covers not only the community at large, but also focuses on several key players who evolved the community into what it is today. Big names like Ken, Azen, PC Chris, Korean DJ, and many others are all extensively featured across the lengthy film, and all have fascinating perspectives on the scene and its evolution.

Plus, thereÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s a healthy dose of rivalry in just about every episode Ã¢â‚¬â€œ you know, to keep things interesting.

YouÃ¢â‚¬â„¢ll also learn about how Melee was never intended to be a competitive fighting game (but actually a party game), how the Smash community didnÃ¢â‚¬â„¢t take wholeheartedly to Super Smash Bros. Brawl, the third iteration which released on the Nintendo Wii, and how Melee champions come and go in the blink of an eye. 

